      "id": "PopularPost159006",
      "post_content": "\"Can be used even when there is no damage to prevent. It prevents the next damage (if any) from the source this turn.\"  \n  \nDon't understand this ruling at all. I thought that there is no damage prevention anymore and reading the full rules confirms that. Today you have to anticipate the damage and pre-emptively put a damage prevention in effect.  \n  \nIt's easy if we talk about spell stack. You play a [Drain Life](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Drain Life) targetting me and in response I activate my COP: Black. My damage prevention anticipation resolves and waits for the next black damage which, if the Drain Life resolves next, is the Drain Life and It will not damage me.  \n  \nBut it's totally different thing with combat. You attack me with your [War Mammoth](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=War Mammoth) and I want to kill him. So I block it with my three [Drudge Skeletons](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Drudge Skeletons). Let's say that I have three untapped [swamp](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=swamp)s and [Circle of Protection: Green](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Circle of Protection: Green). Under old rules you stated how you di... [(see all)](javascript:void(0);)",
